The '''Video DAC''' is a chip on the N64 motherboard that converts the 7-bit-wide synchronous [[Video Interface]] output to analog video.

Early revisions pair a discrete Video DAC (VDC-NUS or VDC-NUS A) with an external encoder (ENC-NUS or S-RGB A) to generate video output.<ref>S-RGB A is only observed on NUS-001(FRA) models. While this encoder is RGB-capable, the necessary amplification components are unpopulated on the motherboard in retail units. S-RGB A lacks S-Video encoding entirely, limiting unmodified NUS-CPU(R)-01 boards to composite output.</ref> Other revisions consolidate these functions into a single integrated chip (DENC-NUS, AVDC-NUS, MAV-NUS).<ref>Later PAL revisions NUS-CPU(P)-03 and -03-1 lack S-Video output due to board-level omissions; the Y (luma) and C (chroma) traces from the MAV-NUS encoder to the Multi Out are severed and the supporting surface-mount components are unpopulated. S-Video output can be restored with a flex cable mod tapping directly from the MAV-NUS.</ref>

== Bus Operation ==

The Video DAC operates at four times the pixel clock frequency. Four consecutive VI clock cycles are multiplexed over the VI bus to form one 21-bit color value per emitted pixel.

* 1 pixel = 4 VI clocks
* 7 bits × 3 channels = 21-bit RGB

[[File:N64videosys.png|thumb|Video DAC bus and waveform diagram. Image from: [https://web.archive.org/web/20090103080549/http://members.optusnet.com.au/eviltim/n64rgb/n64rgb.html Tim Worthington - RGB Video DAC for Nintendo 64]]]

The 4-cycle sequence carries both pixel data and control signals and restarts whenever !DSYNC is low.

The Video Interface transmits control signals every clock during blanking by holding !DSYNC low across multiple VI clock cycles.

{| class="wikitable"
! !! Cycle 0 !! Cycle 1 !! Cycle 2 !! Cycle 3
|-
! !DSYNC
| '''Low''' || '''High''' || '''High''' || '''High'''
|-
! D0
| !Csync || Red 0 || Green 0 || Blue 0
|-
! D1
| !Hsync || Red 1 || Green 1 || Blue 1
|-
! D2
| !Clamp<ref>The !Clamp signal (! = active low) is asserted during the horizontal back porch to restore the DC component of an AC-coupled signal. This "clamping" process re-establishes the black level reference (0 IRE) in this window to stabilize signal brightness. Because the color burst is transmitted concurrently, some sources refer to this period as "clamp/burst."</ref> || Red 2 || Green 2 || Blue 2
|-
! D3
| !Vsync || Red 3 || Green 3 || Blue 3
|-
! D4
| — || Red 4 || Green 4 || Blue 4
|-
! D5
| — || Red 5 || Green 5 || Blue 5
|-
! D6
| — || Red 6 || Green 6 || Blue 6
|}

== Precision ==

The Video DAC outputs 21-bit RGB color. Each pixel period transmits 28 bits (7 bits × 4 cycles), of which 21 bits are used for RGB data. Four of the remaining bits are used for control signaling during blanking; three bits are unused.<ref>Since there are three unused bits in the multiplex sequence, it is unclear why the DAC has only 7 bits of precision instead of 8; no documentation yet found explains this.</ref>

== Reference Clock ==

A quartz crystal resonator on the N64 motherboard supplies the X'tal1 (X1) reference clock to the clock synthesizer (U7 or U17<ref>Early boards use the 8-pin Macronix MX8330MC at U7; later revisions substitute with equivalent MX9911MC. "Funtastic"-era and later models consolidate U7 and U15 into a single 14-pin MX8350 synthesizer at U17.</ref>) in order to generate the VI clock frequency (VCLK).

The N64 utilizes AT-cut crystals sourced from Daishinku Co., Ltd. (KDS)<ref>Corroborated by [https://gbhwdb.gekkio.fi/ Game Boy hardware database] explicitly identifying identical crystals as Daishinku Co., Ltd. (est. 1959 as Daiwa Shinku Kogyosho), [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Nintendo-Famicom-Motherboard-BL.jpg "KDS" markings on Famicom and NES resonators], and an [https://fcc.report/FCC-ID/BKEHAC013/3265207.pdf FCC report] indicating an ongoing supplier relationship between Nintendo and Daishinku. Crystals identical in appearance and marking convention to those positively identified as KDS crystals have been confirmed to appear on at least Game Boy, SNES, Virtual Boy, N64, and Game Boy Color hardware.</ref> with a baseline frequency tolerance of ±30 ppm<ref>X1 and X2 are visually identified as AT-49 hermetically sealed through-hole AT-cut crystal resonators from [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Nintendo-N64-Motherboard-Top.jpg N64 motherboard photography (Evan-Amos, Wikimedia Commons)], consistent with KDS AT-49 package dimensions ([https://www.kds.info/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/2011-2012_032_en.pdf KDS AT-38/AT-49 Datasheet]). ±30 ppm is the base grade frequency tolerance specified for commercial AT-49 crystals by the same manufacturer (KDS AT-38/AT-49 Datasheet). The TXC 9C Series ([https://txccrystal.com/images/pdf/9c.pdf TXC 9C Series Datasheet]) independently corroborates this figure; TXC crystal resonators are confirmed present in N64-derived hardware (iQue Player).</ref>; derived signals inherit this proportional error.

=== Crystal Frequency Derivation ===

[[File:CCIR-1990-Rep.624-4-Table.png|thumb|alt=Chrominance sub-carrier frequencies. M/NTSC: 3,579,545 ± 10 Hz; M/PAL: 3,575,611.49 ± 10 Hz ; B/PAL: 4,433,618.75 ± 5 Hz|Chrominance sub-carrier frequencies. M/NTSC: 3,579,545 ± 10 Hz; M/PAL: 3,575,611.49 ± 10 Hz ; B/PAL: 4,433,618.75 ± 5 Hz. Image from: [http://handle.itu.int/11.1004/020.1000/4.283 CCIR Report 624-4 (1990), Table II]]]

Each regional broadcast standard defines a horizontal line frequency (<math>f_H</math>), from which the chrominance subcarrier frequency (<math>f_{SC}</math>)<ref>The carrier frequency on which color (hue and saturation) is modulated for analog video. Also referred to as colorburst, color subcarrier, or chrominance sub-carrier. Note that "burst" refers specifically to the sample of this subcarrier transmitted during the back porch to establish a phase and frequency reference. Standard NTSC (System M) specifies 9 ± 1 cycles of the carrier wave during burst; PAL (System B/G) specifies 10 ± 1 cycles. Source: [http://handle.itu.int/11.1004/020.1000/4.283 CCIR Report 624-4 (1990), Table I].</ref> is derived as a fixed rational multiple. The X1 resonant frequency is specified as 4 × <math>f_{SC}</math>.

All frequencies are given in hertz (Hz).

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;"
! Standard !! <math>f_H</math> !! <math>f_{SC}</math> : <math>f_H</math> !! <math>f_{SC}</math> !! X1
|-
| '''NTSC''' || <math>\frac{2{,}250{,}000}{143}</math> || <math>f_{SC} = \frac{455}{2} f_H</math> || <math>\frac{315}{88} \times 10^6</math> || <math>\frac{315}{22} \times 10^6</math>
|-
| '''PAL''' || <math>15{,}625</math> || <math>f_{SC} = \left(\frac{1135}{4} + \frac{1}{625}\right) f_H</math> || <math>\frac{17{,}734{,}475}{4}</math> || <math>17{,}734{,}475</math>
|-
| '''MPAL''' || <math>\frac{2{,}250{,}000}{143}</math> || <math>f_{SC} = \frac{909}{4} f_H</math> || <math>\frac{511{,}312{,}500}{143}</math> || <math>\frac{2{,}045{,}250{,}000}{143}</math>
|}

Converted to decimal (Hz):

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;"
! Standard !! <math>f_H</math> !! <math>f_{SC}</math> : <math>f_H</math> !! <math>f_{SC}</math> !! X1
|-
| '''NTSC''' || 15,734.2657 || 227.5 <math>f_H</math> || 3,579,545.4545 || 14,318,181.8182
|-
| '''PAL''' || 15,625 || 283.7516 <math>f_H</math> || 4,433,618.75 || 17,734,475
|-
| '''MPAL''' || 15,734.2657 || 227.25 <math>f_H</math> || 3,575,611.8881 || 14,302,447.5524
|}

=== Clock Synthesis ===
[[File:MX8350-Table.png|thumb|alt=MX8350 functional description and frequency table.|MX8350 functional description and frequency table. Image from: [http://www.datasheet.hk/view_download.php?id=1145313&file=0069%5Cmx8350_566191.pdf IC-ON-LINE - Macronix MX8350 datasheet mirror]]]
[[File:MX8330 video maths.png|thumb|alt=MX8330MC description. FSEL (frequency select) logic and Revision E notice|MX8330 description. FSEL (frequency select) logic and Revision E notice. Image from: [https://wiki.console5.com/tw/images/e/e3/MX8330.pdf Console5 - Macronix MX8330MC datasheet mirror]]]

The clock synthesizer (Macronix MX8330MC / MX9911MC / MX8350) derives the necessary clocks from the X1 crystal input:<ref>'''RCLK''': Rambus clock derived from a second crystal (X2). The output frequency is X2 × 17, with a nominal X2 of 250 MHz ÷ 17 ≈ 14.705882 MHz. This clock is driven via the high-speed, low-voltage swing RSL (Rambus Signaling Logic; sometimes expanded in third-party documentation as "Rambus Signaling Level") '''FSO''' output pin, rather than the TTL-compatible '''FSO/5''' used in VCLK generation (FSC output is also TTL-compatible).</ref>

* '''FSC''': Chrominance subcarrier = X1 ÷ 4
* '''VCLK''': Video clock = X1 × multiplier ÷ 5
'''FSEL (NTSC/!PAL)''':<ref>This pin is marked FSEL on the MX8330MC and MX9911MC datasheets; the equivalent pin on the MX8350 is referred to as '''NTSC/!PAL'''.</ref> Input pin; tied high or low. Selects the VCLK multiplier:

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;"
! Standard !! FSEL Pin State !! Multiplier
|-
| '''NTSC, MPAL'''   || High || 17×
|-
| '''PAL'''    || Low  || 14×
|}

Video clock frequency is calculated using the following formula:

<math>VCLK = \frac{X1 \times \text{Multiplier}}{5}</math>

There are three video clock configurations corresponding to NTSC, PAL, and MPAL:

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;"
! Standard !! FSC (<math>f_{SC}</math>) !! Crystal 1 (X1) !! FSEL (NTSC/!PAL) !! Multiplier !! Divider !! VCLK
|-
| '''NTSC''' || 3.57954545 MHz || 14.31818182 MHz || High || 17 || 5 || 48.68181818 MHz
|-
| '''PAL''' || 4.43361875 MHz || 17.734475 MHz || Low || 14 || 5 || 49.65653 MHz
|-
| '''MPAL''' || 3.57561189 MHz || 14.30244755 MHz || High || 17 || 5 || 48.62832167 MHz
|}

The [[Audio Interface]] also uses this clock.

